# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: carrier-dove-clipper
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] The ***Absalom*** was a wooden ketch that was wrecked at the Macleay River bar at Trial Bay, New South Wales in 1863.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] The *Absalom* was built for the timber trade, and W.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] She spent the early years of her career traveling to the Shoalhaven.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] By 1857 she had moved to include Wollongong.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] She spent much of 1858 traveling to Brisbane Water.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] During 1861 she made trips to the Shoalhaven and Moruya River.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] During one of these trips, she came across two crew members of the *Cambrian Packet*, which had sunk in a squall off Port Aiken.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] The ship's master, Edward Jones, and a seaman named Dalton kept themselves afloat for over an hour before they were rescued by the *Absalom*, which returned them both to Sydney.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] By 1862, the *Absalom* was trading in the Macleay River, with J Fraser as master.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] On 29 March 1863, she was attempting to beat out of the river, but missed stays and ran upon the South Spit at the Heads, and in a few minutes went to pieces.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] Mr McKenzie, the pilot of the area, was quickly in his boat, and rendered all the assistance that could be given.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] All hands were saved, but the vessel and cargo, consisting of more than six hundred bushels of maize, were totally lost.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] The crew were returned to Sydney by the *Woolloomooloo*.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/absalom-1853] The *Absalom* was uninsured, and belonged to Mr J Hubbard.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/acme-1876] The ***Acme*** was a wooden top sail schooner that was driven ashore at Seal Rocks, New South Wales while carrying timber from Camden Haven to Sydney under the command of Captain James Henry Jackson on the 15 July 1876.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] Clarke had the reputation of being a reliable seaman, and claimed to know the area well, so Meade allowed him to take the helm at about 1.30 a.m.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] Shortly afterward, spotting the approach of three huge waves on the starboard quarter, the two men shouted to rouse the crew and endeavored to bring the yacht's head round to clear the southern end of the wave, or at least to receive it bow foremost.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] Before the yacht rounded, the first wave struck, swamping the dingy that was towing astern.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] The second wave threw the yacht on her beam ends and carried away midshipman Fulgombe, and the third wave washed away everyone but Meade, who clung to the wreck for as long as he was able.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] *Aenid* was almost completely submerged, and all that could be seen above the water was the end of the square-sail yard and the rigging.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] Meade, pulled from the wreck by tidal currents, struck out for shore, where he was joined by three of his companions — Clarke and a seaman named Tilly were missing.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] Tilly's body was discovered two days later, close to the shore, but Clarke was never seen again.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/aenid-ship] The yacht was later found washed up on Long Reef, with a portion of her broadside stove in.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Captain **Alfred Bulltop Stormalong** was an American folk hero and the subject of numerous nautical-themed tall tales originating in Massachusetts.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was said to be a sailor and a giant, some 30 feet (9.1 m) tall; he was the master of a huge clipper ship known in various sources as either the *Courser* or the *Tuscarora*, a ship purportedly so tall that it had hinged masts to avoid catching on the Moon.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The name of Stormalong first appeared in a cycle of sea shanties that Stan Hugill, in his *Sea Shanties of the Seven Seas*, traces back to African-American folk songs of the 1830s and '40s.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Bearing names like "Mister Stormalong", "Way Stormalong John", and "Yankee John, Stormalong", these sailors' work songs generally featured praise for a deceased seaman and for his benevolent son.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The tall tales about Stormalong first appeared in the 1911 book *Here's Audacity!* by Frank Shay.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] More tales appeared in the 1933 pamphlet *Old Stormalong Yarns* by C.E.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] New England was where he was beached as a baby, already three fathoms (18 ft) tall.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] According to one telling, he outgrew Cape Cod and moved to Boston, where he signed aboard the first ship that would take him at the age of twelve.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] He had a lifelong rivalry with a Kraken, a huge sea monster from Norse myth; in fact, the Kraken escaped from him in their first encounter, causing a dejected Stormalong to abandon the sea life for life as a farmer somewhere in the Midwest.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Some sources say he had a ship so large that a stable of Arabian horses were aboard for his crew to get from one end of the ship to the other.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Among other things, the ship Alfred was best said to have drilled the course of the Panama Canal by slamming into the Panamanian coast, and to have gotten stuck in the English Channel, which required the crew to grease the ship's hull with soap.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The soap combined with the scraping of the hull against the Gray Cliffs of Dover turned them bright white.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] As Stormalong grew older, he eventually encountered the Kraken again, this time successfully drawing the beast into a whirlpool from which it never escaped.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] The aged Stormalong won the race by several miles, but the stress of handling the wheel through the difficult Atlantic crossing killed him.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong was buried at sea, and Davy Jones himself opened his famous locker to accept Stormalong's body.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Another ending to his life is as follows: While Stormalong was on his Caribbean adventures, he passed by Florida, seeing that there was a tremendous hurricane that tore through his ship.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Ships sailing nearby were being tossed around by the heavy waves.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] Stormalong went overboard and piled as many boats as he could onto his ship.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] When the storm finally wound down, the sailors were dropped back off at Florida.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] After that, he went back on board, unfurling the sails of his ship, seeing if they could be repaired.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A great wind, the last blow of the hurricane, hit the sails, lifting Stormalong and his ship into the sky.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] A third ending to his life takes advantage of the inference that, being a giant, Alfred Bulltop Stormalong was an enormous eater.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/alfred-bulltop-stormalong] It describes a time when his hunger was greater than usual and led him to eat so much food (one variant cites a breakfast of six sharks; it is not definitely known what other variants exist) that he suffered terminal indigestion, causing his magnificent appetite to finish him.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/ambassador-clipper] William Walker built *Ambassador* at Lavender Dry Dock in London.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Though considered a fast ship, *Ambassador* was said to be "very cranky and overmasted".
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/ambassador-clipper] Her first passage to the UK from Fuzhou came during the Tea Race of 1870 under Captain Duggan and took 115 days, a mediocre performance; that same year the fastest tea passage, also from Fuzhou, was made by the clipper *Lahloo* in just 98 days.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/ambassador-clipper] *Ambassador*'s fastest passage between China and England was 108 days, in 1872.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/ambassador-clipper] The wreck is now reduced to a skeletal frame.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ***Andrew Jackson*** was a 1,679-registered-ton medium clipper built by the firm of Irons & Grinnell in Mystic, Connecticut in 1855.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was designed for the shipping firm of J.H.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Brower & Co. to carry cargo intended for sale to participants in the California Gold Rush.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The ship was 220 feet (67 m) in length, had a beam of 41 ft., 2 in., and a draft 22 ft., 3 in.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The vessel was described as "a very handsome, well-designed ship.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] This was one of only three 89-day runs performed by square-rigged ships driving from New York City to California.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] The other two runs were both posted by *Flying Cloud*.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud*'s fastest New York-to-California run had taken 89 days and 8 hours; *Andrew Jackson*'s run was, by four hours, widely acclaimed in the newspapers as the fastest in history.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some clipper ship authorities, including Howe and Matthews, assert that *Andrew Jackson* did not actually set the record described above.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] They concede, however, that this medium clipper, perhaps not naturally as fast as *Flying Cloud*, achieved a remarkable passage as the result of a combination of hard driving by the captain and favorable winds.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] However, after careful scrutiny of the logbooks, one author, Carl C.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Cutler, concludes that a case can be made for either *Flying Cloud* or *Andrew Jackson* holding the record.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] Some will consider the passage from pilot-to-pilot as the appropriate indicator of fastest sailing performance around Cape Horn.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/andrew-jackson-clipper] *Flying Cloud* holds the record time for a passage anchor-to-anchor from New York to San Francisco, of 89 days 8 hours, while *Andrew Jackson'*s completed passage anchor-to-anchor may have been as long as 89 days 20 hours.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] The schooner ***Anglona*** was the first American opium clipper.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] She sailed in the Chinese coastal trade in the 1840s, and had a famous race with the schooner *Ariel* around Lintin Island.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes was interested in fast schooners for clipper and coastal service in China.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] The first clipper which Forbes sent to China, the *Rose*, foundered in the July typhoon of 1841.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Forbes purchased *Anglona* at Brown & Bell's New York yard for Russell & Co. for use as a despatch boat between Hong Kong, Macao, and Whampoa.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Other American pilot boat models sent to China in the 1840s included the *Zephyr* and the *Spec*, also built on the New York model.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Shortly after Shanghai opened to foreign trade, three Boston pilot boats were sent: the 90 ton *Golden Gate*, the 90 ton *Siren*, and the 75 ton *Daniel Webster*, which served as pilot boats in the Yangtze River.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Within two weeks of purchase, *Anglona* sailed for China under Captain Turner.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] She arrived at Cape Horn in 61 days, and Java Head in 95 days.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Russell & Co put *Anglona* in service on the Canton River until the new treaty ports opened, at which time she was put in the coastal trade.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Captain Turner did not serve long, as he was knocked overboard by the mainboom during a sudden jibe, and drowned.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] In 1843, *Anglona* was under command of Capt.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Adamson; in 1844 she was under Captain Macfarlane.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] On September 20, 1841, *Anglona* left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo of rice from Macao bound for the East Coast; on Dec.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] 2, she left Hong Kong with a 108-ton cargo from Macao of opium or specie bound for Namoa.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Lee, the designer of the *Rose*, wanted to know why Forbes hadn't come to him for a clipper schooner instead, and got Forbes to agree to taking a half interest in one of his schooners if it could beat the *Anglona*.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] The *Ariel*, a new 92-ton schooner built by Sprague & James at Medford, MA was taken out for a trial in 1841 out of Lewis Wharf in Boston Harbor, against the 30 ton schooner-yacht *Breeze*, which had been built for Forbes by Daniel C.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] The wind had freshened and was blowing in hard puffs.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] He had suggested taking in a second reef, but his companions assured him the wind would slacken as they approached the harbor.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] In stays off Sound Point Beacon, the Ariel laid down before she could get way on for a tack towards Long Island, and sank in seven fathoms of water.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] When *Ariel* was refloated, Lee agreed to reduce the rig, and cut down the masts as per Forbes’ suggestion.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Ariel* was then sent to China under Capt.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] Poor, making an 80-day passage to Anjer.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] The race between *Ariel* and *Anglona* was about 40 mi., from Macao Roads around Lintin and back, for stakes of $1,000 and Forbes’ agreement to take half-interest in *Ariel* if she won.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* was much stronger sailing to windward, due to the shallow draft of *Ariel,* and took the lead until rounding the island.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] At that point, *Ariel* set a large flying square sail and topsail.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/anglona-clipper] *Anglona* had no ballooning sails for running downwind, and was beaten by 17 minutes.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] Her voyage from New York to San Francisco in 1860 under Captain Montell was more fortunate, and she arrived in 127 days.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] In 1862, she took a cargo of wheat from San Francisco to Queenstown, Australia, in 124 days.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] Liverpool to Melbourne, 78 days, in 1858.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] Melbourne to Valparaíso, 30 or 32 days, under Captain Theodore Corner, very close to the record.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] In 1862, *Carrier Dove* sailed in the transatlantic trade under Captain Nash and Captain Jackson.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] She went ashore at Portmagee, County Kerry, in February 1863, but was repaired and auctioned to her former owners, Trask & Dearborn.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] Also in 1863, she "collided with another vessel in the Mersey" that year, requiring assistance from three steam-tugs.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] In 1865, while en route from Shields, England, laden with coal and general cargo, she went ashore on Governors Island in New York Harbor, just outside her destination, New York City.
[src:carrier-dove-clipper/carrier-dove-clipper] Her cargo was taken the rest of the way to the wharves by lighter.
